<font color="#FF0000">MYTHS AND TRUTHS</font><br>
<tt>Sat Jan 11 16:53:27 US/Eastern 1997
</tt><p>
To whom it may concern:<br>
     After viewing this discussion and having participated in it, I have the following comments:<br>
1.  Movies are nice to view and sometimes entertaining, but are no substsitute for the real film.  Yes, there are some great movies on the war and these shouldn't be ignored.  They have truth and artisitic merit in them.  Movies are the viewpoint of the person that created them and express that person's view.  I value the real films of battle and of the men taken during the war.  They are vivid images of that moment in time captured forever, open to any interpretation when viewed.  As a teacher, I value newsreels and combat camera footage of the war to demonstrate what it was like.  The interviews with soldiers done then are not tainted by 30 years of livings since then, which is important, but not always relevant to the study of the attitude of a period.  Movies should only be used as a small segment of the study of Vietnam.<br>
2.  Myths and facts on the war have no agenda.  There is no left or right wing agenda in the truth.  What needs to be focused on is the truth.  The Vietnam Vet is not a drugged, violent, unemployed, maniac criminal loser.  The facts and I STRESS that everyone view the FACT are the following:<br>
A.  Vietnam Vets are less likely to be jailed for violent crimes-only 1/2 of 1 percent of Vietnam vets have been jailed for crimes.<br>
B.  97% of Vietnam era vets were honorably discharged from the service.<br>
C.  85% of vets made a successful transition to civilian life, which was not easy to do.<br>
D.  The personal income of Nam Vets exceeds that of the non-veteran same age group by 18%.<br>
E.  Vietnam vets have a lower unemployment rate, then the same age group which didn't serve.<br>
F.  2/3 of the men in Nam were volunteers, compared to 2/3 of World War II vets which were drafted.  70% of the men killed in Nam were volunteers.  Not everyone was a draftee.<br>
G.  Accordin to testimony to the committee on Veterans Affairs, The US Senate-100rd Congress, Second Session by Dr.<br>
Houk:only about 9,000 vets have killed themselves.  Vets are less likely to kill themselves then non-vets.<br>
H.  According to Gov't studies, there was and still is no difference in drug usuage between Nam Vets and non-vets of the same age group.<br>
I.  American soldiers were not bloodthirsty killers!!!!!<br>
Yes, there was killings such as My Lai and other places, but nowhere on the scale that many people believe.  According to Col. Harry G. Summers (editor of Vietnam Magazine) in his book The Vietnam War Alamanac, the number of men charged with serious crimes against civilians was 201 for the Army and 77 for the Marines.  Instead most Americans were helpful to the Vietnamese civilians.  I know as a personal fact, that Navy Seabees (engineers) and many Marines made it a personal point to do acts of kindness for the civilian population.  There were Navy and Marine Corp civil action teams that were labeled by the press and the military as being the military's Peace Corp.  I am sure the Army can attest to the same.  Just as a thought also, more than 100 men were executed according to military record for crimes against civilains during World War II.<br>
J.  Not everyone in Vietnam was a 18 year old kid.  According to the Combat Area Casualty File, which is the basis for the data and names used of the Vietnam Veterans Memorial in Washington DC the averaged age among enlisted men killed was 22.37 years.  Among officers it was 28.43 years and among MOS 11B (infantry) it was 22.55 years.  The average of all casualties, assuming the 58,000 dead are a random sample of the 2.6 million that served, is 23.11 years old.<br>
I.  Vietnam was  as a intense war as World War II.  World War II was a bad war, but the average infantryman in Nam had 240 days of combat, while the average infantryman in the pacific in World War II had 40 days of <br>
combat.<br>
J.  Yes, race was a problem then and unfortunately it still is a problem today.  Blacks were not cannon fodder in Vietnam.  African American suffered 12.5 of the deaths, during a time when the percentage of blacks of military age <br>
was 13.5% of the population.  Yes, blacks suffered high casualties at certain times of the war, but this was because many of them (34%) volunteered for front line combat units.  Many blacks volunteered an/or signed up for tough combat units like the Marines or Airborne, 20 of them even won the Medal of Honor. There was not a disproportinate number of blacks killed in Vietnam.  86% of the dead were caucasians.<br>
Two prominent sociologists, Charles Moskos and John Sidney Butler have proved that blacks were not used as cannon fodder.<br>
My facts come from many sources:<br>
1.Veterans of Foreign Wars Magazine-March 1993<br>
2. The Vietnam War Almanac by Col. Harry G. Summers<br>
3. Speech of Lt. Gen Barry McCaffrey, assistant to the Chairman of the Joint Chiefs of Staff, to the vets and visitors at the Wall on Memorial Day 1993.  It was well researched and published in the Pentagram on June 4, 1993.<br>
4. Dept of Labor Study, October 1994.<br>
5. Vietnam Helicopter Pilots Association -Historical Reference Directory -Volume 2A.<br>
There is also a web site called Statistics of the Vietnam War.<br>
3.  As a teacher, writer and historian, I am horrified on how many mistruths on Nam Vets are presented as fact. These mistruths will one day become accepted knowledge on Vietnam if not set straight.  This is what the myth and facts argument is all about.  Vietnam Vets must be shown as the stable men and women they are.  This is the quest of Vietnam Vet B. G. Burkett, a Dallas financial adviser who helped raise funds for the Texas memorial.  We need to hear true stories of Vietnam from the real vets (not the phony ones Burkett exposes) who were there.  This is not an agenda, this is the truth.  Our children need to know Nam Vets are stable, productive citizens that served their country.<br>
This dialog has nothing to do with the media, Hollywood or any fingerpointing.  It should be about real facts and teaching the right things to America's children. Somehow (no fingerpointing) many false beliefs have filled the common knowledge of America and these must be changed.  There are a million true stories of decent men and women who fought the<br>
war and tried to support the troops and end it at home.  These facts and true stories are what America needs to hear, not the lies and mistruths.    
<p><code>--   (Concerned Teacher and Historian) </code><p>


